   <text>
      <body>
         <div>
            <head>3.8.1885 Montag</head>
            <p>
               <placeName type="write" key="49289">Rigi Kaltbad</placeName>. August 3 1885 Monday.</p>
            <p>Took my bath before breakfast and after breakfast sat by the music and read. Then
               started for First with <persName key="104">Gee</persName>. But she declared she was
               dead tired as soon as we had gone a few steps; so I went home and took a walk to the
               Känzeli and a little further down with <persName key="103">Mamma</persName>. At
               dinner made acquaintance of young <persName key="7851">Swabach</persName>
               <note type="reg">Paul</note>. His parents are the Swabachers<note type="reg">
                  <persName key="18297">Leonie</persName> und <persName key="18296">Julius</persName>
               </note> of the <name type="work" key="80987">société de Berlin </name>. He told me
                  <persName key="1857">Gerard</persName> the sécrétaire of <persName key="1858">the
                  Empress</persName>
               <note type="reg">Augusta</note> and <persName key="1859">Madame
                  Novikoff</persName> had written it. His brother is a professor or is going to be
               one; that I could not make out. They live 7 Wilhelmsplatz in the Palais
                  Radziwill<note type="reg">
                  <placeName key="58186">Reichskanzlerpalais</placeName>
               </note>; so they must be very rich. They are Jews
               as <persName key="103">Mamma</persName> says. In the afternoon played cards and
               billards with <persName key="7851">Swabach</persName> and an American. After Dinner I
               numérohéd <name type="work" key="28586">Roland</name>
               <note type="reg">
                  <persName key="103">Kessler</persName>
               </note> and read the disclosure scene in the
               piece, which <persName key="103">Mamma</persName> has very much improved. <persName key="7851">S.</persName> says <persName key="1857">Gérard</persName> wrote the
               whole information containedined in the <name type="work" key="80987">Société de
                  Berlin</name> to <persName key="9594">Gambetta</persName> in private letters and
               that when <persName key="9594">Gambetta</persName> died <persName key="17472">Madame
                  Adam</persName> bought the letters and out of the information fabriquéd the <name type="work" key="80987">book</name>. Enfin, so many people; so many versions, like
               about <name type="work" key="28586">Rol.</name> which <persName key="11532">Mad. de
                  Kolemine</persName>, <persName key="4200">Princess Ratzwill</persName>; <persName key="1862">Princess Serge Lydie Puschkoff</persName> and dozens of others were
               said in the papers to have written. Although this book has had such success
                  <placeName key="67188">Lemarre</placeName> will not pay anything and always evades
               the question when asked.</p>
